Wow, after having been here twice, I'm surprised I have yet to review ... and I only find it appropriate to use Gary Danko to celebrate my 900th review! This place is absolutely amazing in so many grand and subtle ways as noted by the many patrons who have frequented this place and made it such an amazing debut on Yelp. The reservations are tough but not impossible and quite a bit better than $80/person you will pay at Ana Madara across the plaza. They have a few prix fixe options starting with a 3 course meal to a 5 course meal. I feel that 4 courses usually does the job which costs around $90/person without any wine pairings. I don't usually find it worthy for wine pairing at my meal because I had done it once and was severely unimpressed. With the type of prices GD charges, I'm not surprised that I was turned off from it. Regardless the meal was excellent. The last time I went, the bf made late reservations on my birthday to go to Gary Danko. It was TRULY a surprise because we got to SF at 9:30 PM and I was thinking in my head what he was up to on a Tuesday night... As usual, the service was impeccable and cannot be disputed. Everything from the greeting to the entry to the wine pouring was perfect down to the last drop. The presentation was incredible and their duck and beef are good but their seafood platters are even better. I love the lamb, however it's presented on the menu, and that extra $5 you pay for the flaming dessert is SO WORTH IT. Please order it and be done with it! I love that they give you coffee cake to go at the end of the night to enjoy with your coffee the next day. I love that they have on the house desserts after your dessert choice, I love that they give you random tidbits of food in between that's not to clean your palate; and most of all I love that they always ask me in a subtle, non awkward way that doesn't catch me mid-bite or mid-chewing how my food is and if I need anything extra. That's service. I love GD. Perhaps not as much as French Laundry but then again who compares ... regardless it is one of my absolute favorites. The end.

Intimate, cozy, plush yet unpretentious with impeccable service and truly spectacular food. If you're looking for one of the finest dining experiences in the city, Gary Danko should be at the top of your list. You can choose a la carte or the chef's 5-course tasting menu. I decided to graze through the menu on my own to create my own 5-course menu, per the suggestion of my girlfriend who'd been there twice. I doubted her but she assured me that if we ordered 3 appetizers, 1 fish and 1 meat/fowl dish it wouldn't be too much since they balance the portions so it's the perfect meal. It was indeed spectacular - nouvelle cuisine in that the portions were small (but not mice-sized by any means) and expertly prepared with fresh and innovative ingredients and flavors. Started with the Sonoma foie gras which was out of this world, then onto the spring tarte with spring vegetables (outstanding), then lobster and rock shrimp in risotto surrounded by a spring pea reduction (heavenly) and then one perfectly prepared sea scallop (again, in a spring pea reduction/oil). Finished with a perfectly prepared and savory duck. Don't miss the spring tarte & the Sonoma foie gras. All the menu items I had were terrific but these were the standouts. Perfect service, attentive without being hovering as well as elegant without being stuffy. It's a fine line and some restaurants (like Fleur de Lys) could learn from Gary Danko and his excellent staff. I hope Gary Danko wins the James Beard award tomorrow night. Now that I have my first time at his restaurant under my belt, he deserves the honor. PS I also got to wear my new & classically stunning Hugo Boss Black label dress from GIlt.com, a company I wish I could review but Yelp won't let me/doesn't recognize it.

I'm a believer now after dining at MM, Gary Danko is a solid 5 stars and sets the bar for all restaurants in the city. Their menu is vast and you can create any combo to your liking. Like all entrees? OK. Want all appetizers? OK. Dessert type of person? OK. Price? ALL THE SAME. For 2-3 hours, you get an experience like you're on top of the world and every person is catering to your needs and liking, while dining on delectable dishes with fresh and flavorful ingredients. Service is unmatched and the food is consistent. If you like fine dining and good food for a reasonable price, GD is a MUST.

200th Review! Might as well make it a special one! Gary Danko is almost as synonymous to San Francisco, as Alice Waters is to the Berkley area. A past James Beard award winner, Gary Danko has set the bar quite high. Known for precision food and excellent service, Gary Danko met my expectations and exceeded them if possible. PHOTOS of all dishes included. The meal started out with an amuse bouche of pea and ramp (I think) soup with a lobster tempura ball. The soup was sweet and delicate, and the lobster was sweet and salty at the same time. Perfect way to start the meal, along with a complimentary glass of rose champagne. The next amuse, was a buckwheat bilini topped with creme fraiche, smoked salmon and osetra caviar. Although smoked salmon and caviar are a classic combination, the addition of the buckwheat bilini gave a nice subtle nutty flavor. The risotto tasted like a bowl of spring. Nice creamy risotto with a little bit of bite to it, was paired with peas and asparagus at the peak of flavor. The lobster and rock shrimp were nice and sweet. The shimeji mushrooms provided an earthy balance. The roast Maine lobster is a sight to behold. The lobster is sweet and briny, the potato puree super creamy, while the black trumpet mushrooms and edamame give a textural balance. The horseradish crusted salmon is one of Gary Danko's signature dishes. Unforunately, this was my least favorite dish of the night. The horseradish was lacking the spicy kick I was expecting, and the pickled cucumbers and carrots seemed to overpower the delicate flavor of the salmon. The lamb two ways provided both a textural and flavor difference. The loin had a more firm texture with a "meatier" taste, while the shoulder was more tender but had a "gameyness" expected from lamb. The bison had a real "beefy" flavor, and although cooked medium rare had a little chew to it. The cipollini onions were a little too sweet for my taste, while the trumpet mushrooms added another hearty flavor and texture. The chocolate souffle with two sauces was nice and light on top, and oozing on the bottom. This is a super rich dessert, but perfect for chocoholics. The trio of creme brulee was a definite winner. The creme brulee was more on the custard side, instead of being firm, just the way I like it. The butterscotch creme brulee was absolutely fabulous. The chocolate creme brulee was on the thin side, while most of the chocolate creme brulee's I've had in the past are real thick like pudding. The meal ended with a small platter of petit fours. The citrus cookies were a good way to cut through the richness of the meal. I was lucky enough to be given a signed copy of the menu by Gary Danko, along with some small gifts including small bottles of their hand soap and lotion, a monogrammed purse holder, and a Gary Danko wine key. I highly recommend Gary Danko for any food lover, and will be back again in the future.

I don't like how they give those muffins to us but not the guy? Weird... I would feel left out if I was the guy. The check was actually not as expensive as I though it would be. The total was only $334 with tips it was $404. This was honestly the LONGEST dinner ever! 3 1/2 hours! We stayed til closing. Everything from service to main courses were spot on. There is almost no point of reviewing this because Yelp has already spoken. But this was one of the best fine dining experiences I've ever had, so it would be unfair to Gary Danko if I didn't give them a glowing review here. Although prix fixe tasting menus are sometimes fun, I loved the option here of being able to concept of essentially creating one's own tasting menu from a litany of options. Combine it in any way you see fit. Custom tailoring your tasting menu like this I think is a nice balance of ensuring you'll love your food, while still allowing one to try some new things. I went with the girlfriend and we both had the 5 course tasting menu and even added some supplemental courses because everything looked so good. We basically shared something like 13 courses. Unlike most fine dining restaurants, this actually felt like a wonderful value. Yes it cost a lot of money, but it felt worth every penny. The portion sizes were very ample, the ingredients were high end, presentation was on point, romantic atmosphere. The dishes were complex without feeling overwrought and muddled. Flavors ranged from subtle to bold depending on the course. The dishes we picked were wildly different with all sorts of international influences. It would seem like a lot of it wouldn't go together in a cohesive meal, but the glue that tied everything together was everything was goddamn delicious. And made with such skill. Just a perfect balance of flavors in every dish, nothing overpowering anything else, everything working in unison. Some serious thought went into these dishes. I feel like one can judge the skill of the kitchen from how they make a risotto. I can't even count the number of restaurants who give what appears to be rice-a-roni and call it risotto. If it can be made into a molded shape, it's not risotto. Here it was creamy and just the right texture. Of course, this is just one example. Every dish seemed to be done just perfectly. Probably the only disappointment I had was their famous chocolate souffle - cool presentation, but to me it tasted a bit boring - a one note dish. But 1 dish being blah and 12 dishes being incredible is quite a batting average. The service was great. Our guy was so friendly. He was attentive and professional, but also with a nice casual touch which made us feel comfortable and welcome in the restaurant. Sometimes at fine dining places I can feel out of place. I felt welcome to be here and like I was being taken care of. My only complaint would be there was a group of other diners there who were being obnoxiously loud and disrespectful. I wish that perhaps the service staff could have done something to keep them at bay. They were creating a distraction in the restaurant to the point many tables were looking at each other with the "what the hell is wrong with those people" faces. I know they paid money to be there too, but when things get to the point where it is threatening other people's experience, something should be done by the restaurant to the best of their ability. But other than that, which is really more of a complaint about some crazy bastards than the restaurant itself, it was a flawless dining experience. The food is the most important thing and it was some of the best I ever had.

The reservations are tough but not impossible and quite a bit better than $80/person you will pay at Ana Madara across the plaza. They have a few prix fixe options starting with a 3 course meal to a 5 course meal. I feel that 4 courses usually does the job which costs around $90/person without any wine pairings.

    I love GD. Perhaps not as much as French Laundry but then again who compares ... regardless it is one of my absolute favorites. The end.

    Intimate, cozy, plush yet unpretentious with impeccable service and truly spectacular food. If you're looking for one of the finest dining experiences in the city, Gary Danko should be at the top of your list.

    You can choose a la carte or the chef's 5-course tasting menu. I decided to graze through the menu on my own to create my own 5-course menu, per the suggestion of my girlfriend who'd been there twice.

    I doubted her but she assured me that if we ordered 3 appetizers, 1 fish and 1 meat/fowl dish it wouldn't be too much since they balance the portions so it's the perfect meal. It was indeed spectacular - nouvelle cuisine in that the portions were small (but not mice-sized by any means) and expertly prepared with fresh and innovative ingredients and flavors.

    Started with the Sonoma foie gras which was out of this world, then onto the spring tarte with spring vegetables (outstanding), then lobster and rock shrimp in risotto surrounded by a spring pea reduction (heavenly) and then one perfectly prepared sea scallop (again, in a spring pea reduction/oil). Finished with a perfectly prepared and savory duck.

    Don't miss the spring tarte & the Sonoma foie gras. All the menu items I had were terrific but these were the standouts.

    Perfect service, attentive without being hovering as well as elegant without being stuffy. It's a fine line and some restaurants (like Fleur de Lys) could learn from Gary Danko and his excellent staff.

    I hope Gary Danko wins the James Beard award tomorrow night. Now that I have my first time at his restaurant under my belt, he deserves the honor.

    PS I also got to wear my new & classically stunning Hugo Boss Black label dress from GIlt.com, a company I wish I could review but Yelp won't let me/doesn't recognize it.

    5/10/2010

    15 photos

    200th Review! Might as well make it a special one!

    Gary Danko is almost as synonymous to San Francisco, as Alice Waters is to the Berkley area.

    A past James Beard award winner, Gary Danko has set the bar quite high. Known for precision food and excellent service, Gary Danko met my expectations and exceeded them if possible.

    PHOTOS of all dishes included.

    The meal started out with an amuse bouche of pea and ramp (I think) soup with a lobster tempura ball. The soup was sweet and delicate, and the lobster was sweet and salty at the same time. Perfect way to start the meal, along with a complimentary glass of rose champagne.

    The next amuse, was a buckwheat bilini topped with creme fraiche, smoked salmon and osetra caviar. Although smoked salmon and caviar are a classic combination, the addition of the buckwheat bilini gave a nice subtle nutty flavor.

    The risotto tasted like a bowl of spring. Nice creamy risotto with a little bit of bite to it, was paired with peas and asparagus at the peak of flavor. The lobster and rock shrimp were nice and sweet. The shimeji mushrooms provided an earthy balance.

    The roast Maine lobster is a sight to behold. The lobster is sweet and briny, the potato puree super creamy, while the black trumpet mushrooms and edamame give a textural balance.

    The horseradish crusted salmon is one of Gary Danko's signature dishes. Unforunately, this was my least favorite dish of the night. The horseradish was lacking the spicy kick I was expecting, and the pickled cucumbers and carrots seemed to overpower the delicate flavor of the salmon.

    The lamb two ways provided both a textural and flavor difference. The loin had a more firm texture with a "meatier" taste, while the shoulder was more tender but had a "gameyness" expected from lamb.

    The bison had a real "beefy" flavor, and although cooked medium rare had a little chew to it. The cipollini onions were a little too sweet for my taste, while the trumpet mushrooms added another hearty flavor and texture.

    The chocolate souffle with two sauces was nice and light on top, and oozing on the bottom. This is a super rich dessert, but perfect for chocoholics.

    The trio of creme brulee was a definite winner. The creme brulee was more on the custard side, instead of being firm, just the way I like it. The butterscotch creme brulee was absolutely fabulous. The chocolate creme brulee was on the thin side, while most of the chocolate creme brulee's I've had in the past are real thick like pudding.

    The meal ended with a small platter of petit fours. The citrus cookies were a good way to cut through the richness of the meal.

    I was lucky enough to be given a signed copy of the menu by Gary Danko, along with some small gifts including small bottles of their hand soap and lotion, a monogrammed purse holder, and a Gary Danko wine key.

    I highly recommend Gary Danko for any food lover, and will be back again in the future.

    There is almost no point of reviewing this because Yelp has already spoken. But this was one of the best fine dining experiences I've ever had, so it would be unfair to Gary Danko if I didn't give them a glowing review here.

    Although prix fixe tasting menus are sometimes fun, I loved the option here of being able to concept of essentially creating one's own tasting menu from a litany of options. Combine it in any way you see fit. Custom tailoring your tasting menu like this I think is a nice balance of ensuring you'll love your food, while still allowing one to try some new things.

    I went with the girlfriend and we both had the 5 course tasting menu and even added some supplemental courses because everything looked so good. We basically shared something like 13 courses.

    Unlike most fine dining restaurants, this actually felt like a wonderful value. Yes it cost a lot of money, but it felt worth every penny. The portion sizes were very ample, the ingredients were high end, presentation was on point, romantic atmosphere. The dishes were complex without feeling overwrought and muddled. Flavors ranged from subtle to bold depending on the course. The dishes we picked were wildly different with all sorts of international influences. It would seem like a lot of it wouldn't go together in a cohesive meal, but the glue that tied everything together was everything was goddamn delicious. And made with such skill. Just a perfect balance of flavors in every dish, nothing overpowering anything else, everything working in unison. Some serious thought went into these dishes.

    I feel like one can judge the skill of the kitchen from how they make a risotto. I can't even count the number of restaurants who give what appears to be rice-a-roni and call it risotto. If it can be made into a molded shape, it's not risotto. Here it was creamy and just the right texture. Of course, this is just one example. Every dish seemed to be done just perfectly. Probably the only disappointment I had was their famous chocolate souffle - cool presentation, but to me it tasted a bit boring - a one note dish. But 1 dish being blah and 12 dishes being incredible is quite a batting average.

    The service was great. Our guy was so friendly. He was attentive and professional, but also with a nice casual touch which made us feel comfortable and welcome in the restaurant. Sometimes at fine dining places I can feel out of place. I felt welcome to be here and like I was being taken care of.

    My only complaint would be there was a group of other diners there who were being obnoxiously loud and disrespectful. I wish that perhaps the service staff could have done something to keep them at bay. They were creating a distraction in the restaurant to the point many tables were looking at each other with the "what the hell is wrong with those people" faces. I know they paid money to be there too, but when things get to the point where it is threatening other people's experience, something should be done by the restaurant to the best of their ability.

    But other than that, which is really more of a complaint about some crazy bastards than the restaurant itself, it was a flawless dining experience. The food is the most important thing and it was some of the best I ever had.
